{"abt 1305–":"omkring 1305–Afdød","1300–Male":"1300–Afdød","1325–Male":"1325–Afdød","1305–Female":"1305–Afdød","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","abt 1325":"omkring 1325","1325":"1325","abt 1305":"omkring 1305","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","of London, Lond., Eng":"London, England, United Kingdom","London, Lond., Eng.":"London, England, United Kingdom","Wem, Shropshire, England":"Wem, Shropshire, England"},"nl":{"abt 1305–":"circa 1305–Overleden","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1325–Male":"1325–Overleden","1305–Female":"1305–Overleden","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","abt 1325":"circa 1325","1325":"1325","abt 1305":"circa 1305","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","of London, Lond., Eng":"London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London, Lond., Eng.":"London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wem, Shropshire, England":"Wem, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"abt 1305–":"about 1305–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1325–Male":"1325–Deceased","1305–Female":"1305–Deceased","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","abt 1325":"about 1325","1325":"1325","abt 1305":"about 1305","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","of London, Lond., Eng":"London, England, United Kingdom","London, Lond., Eng.":"London, England, United Kingdom","Wem, Shropshire, England":"Wem, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hend","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: (i) nickname from Middle English  <i>hende</i> (Old English  <i>gehænd</i>) ‘courtly, courteous, refined’. (ii) relationship name, perhaps occasionally a variant of   Henn   (a pet form of Henry) with an excrescent  <i>-d</i>. Compare the pet form  <i>Hendekin</i> (  see  Henkin  ) and the patronymic surname   Henderson   for  <i>Henryson</i>.","2  English: variant of   End   with a prosthetic  <i>H-</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Henkin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Doron, Hyman.","English (Middlesex): from the Middle English personal name <i>Henekin</i>, <i>Hendekin</i>, a pet form of   Henry  . Compare   Hankin   1 and   Henn  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metronymic from the female personal name <i>Khenke</i> (a pet form of Yiddish <i>Khane</i>, from Hebrew <i>Ḥanna</i>; see   Hanna   6) + the Slavic possessive suffix <i>-in</i>."]},{"name":"End","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>(atten) ende</i>, denoting someone who lived at the end of a village or other settlement."]},{"name":"Henderson","meanings":["English and Scottish: usually from Middle English and Older Scots <i>Hener(i)son</i> ‘Henry's son’, occasionally from Middle English <i>Hendeson</i> ‘son of <i>Hen</i>’, a pet form of   Henry  , both with an intrusive <i>-d-</i>. Compare   Hendrie  . In Scotland <i>Henderson</i> was sometimes substituted for   McKendrick  ."]},{"name":"Henn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Otto, Siegfried, Ulrike, Aloysius, Bernhard, Heinz, Hermann, Herta, Jurgen, Kurt, Manfred.","English: from the personal name <i>Henn</i>, which, like <i>Hann</i>, was a pet form of <i>Henry</i>. Compare   Henkin  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>hen(ne)</i> ‘hen’ (Old English <i>henn</i>, related to <i>hana</i> ‘cock’), for someone thought to resemble a hen in some way, or perhaps from Middle English <i>hen</i> ‘poor man, rascal’."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":10,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":23,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":32,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Hend was born about 1305, in London, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with John Hend. She died in Wem, Shropshire, England."},"et":{"abt 1305–":"umbes 1305–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1305–Female":"1305